egion notorious for gang activity, according to federal officials—he found significantly less gang membership and activity than common fearmongering claims would have us believe. Instead, he witnessed how the gang label was used to criminalize youth of Mexican descent—to justify the overrepresentation of Latinos in the justice system, the implementation of punitive practices in the school system, and the request for additional resources by law enforcement.In The Gang Paradox, Durán analyzes the impact of deportation, incarceration, and racialized perceptions of criminality on Latino families and youth along the border. He draws on ethnography, archival research, official data sources, and interviews with practitioners and community members to present a compelling portrait of Latino residents’ struggles amid deep structural disadvantages. Durán, himself a former gang member, offers keen insights into youth experience with schools, juvenile probation, and law enforcement. The Gang Paradox is a powerful community study that sheds new light on intertwined criminalization and racialization, with policy relevance toward issues of gangs, juvenile delinquency, and the lack of resources in border regions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 0aCrimezMexican-American Border Region. 0aGangszMexican-American Border Region. 0aYouthzMexican-American Border RegionxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP Single-User eBook-Package 2018z978311070863908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060660740uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/dura1810640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231543439423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231543439/original  a978-3-11-060660-7  C